# Infrastructure Constraints

> **This is a bible file.** See `doc-governance.mdc` — it may not be edited without explicit user approval.

---

## The Hard Rule: Kubernetes-Native

**WellBe workloads are Kubernetes-native. Fly.io, standalone Docker-run services, and PaaS container platforms are not valid deployment targets.**

This applies to every environment except local developer workstations.

---

## What This Means in Practice

| Context | Valid | Not valid |
|---|---|---|
| Local dev — data services (Postgres, Redis, MinIO, Temporal, ZITADEL) | Docker Compose | — |
| Local dev — application services | `uv run` directly, OR `k3d`/`KinD` | Fly.io, `docker run`, `docker-compose up` for app workloads |
| Staging | Kubernetes cluster | Fly.io, Render, Railway, managed container PaaS |
| Production | Kubernetes cluster (EKS / GKE / self-hosted k3s) | Fly.io, Heroku, Render, standalone Docker |

---

## Required K8s Infrastructure

All of the following are part of the standard deployment:

- **CloudNativePG** — Postgres HA operator. Not managed cloud RDS/Cloud SQL.
- **Cilium** — eBPF networking + network policies + mTLS between services
- **Karpenter** — node autoscaling
- **Flux** (or Argo CD) — GitOps delivery; no manual `kubectl apply` in staging or prod
- **External Secrets Operator** — sync OpenBao secrets to K8s workloads
- **OpenBao** — secrets store (dynamic DB creds, API keys, PKI)

---

## Helm Mandate

**Every Kubernetes object in every environment (local k3d/KinD, staging, production) must be managed through a Helm chart.**

| Approach | Valid |
|---|---|
| Helm chart (local, published, or OCI) | ✅ |
| Helm + Helmfile for multi-chart orchestration | ✅ |
| Kustomize patches on top of a Helm-rendered base | ✅ (as post-render only) |
| Raw YAML applied with `kubectl apply` | ❌ |
| Kustomize-only (no Helm base) | ❌ |
| OpenTofu `kubernetes_manifest` resource | ❌ |
| Flux `HelmRelease` CRD (Helm under GitOps) | ✅ |

This applies to application workloads, operators, CRDs, namespaces, RBAC objects, NetworkPolicies, and any other K8s resource. No exceptions without explicit user approval.

---

## Agent Rules

1. When proposing a deployment approach, always assume Kubernetes. Do not propose Fly.io, Render, Railway, Heroku, or other PaaS platforms.
2. When proposing local development setup, Docker Compose is valid for **data services only** (Postgres, Redis, MinIO, Temporal server, ZITADEL). Application workloads run via `uv` or `k3d`.
3. When writing `infra/` IaC, all Kubernetes objects MUST be defined and deployed via Helm charts. Raw `kubectl apply` of standalone YAML manifests, Kustomize-only deployments, and ad-hoc object creation are not valid in any environment. OpenTofu is used for cluster provisioning only — not for applying K8s objects directly.
4. When proposing CI/CD, target GitHub Actions + Flux (GitOps push to cluster), not PaaS deploy hooks.
5. Do not suggest "start with Fly.io and migrate to K8s later." The workloads are K8s-native from day one.

---

## Rationale

The system's workload profile (durable Temporal workflows, Cilium mTLS between PHI-handling services, per-service Postgres roles, CloudNativePG HA, C10 Safety Gate in an isolated namespace) is fundamentally Kubernetes-native. Deploying to a PaaS container platform would require re-architecting the networking, secrets, and database HA patterns at the time of migration — removing any short-term simplicity benefit.
